<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-61-0510 </DOCNO><TEXT>Parental age effects on offspring are important because of i) the needfor accurate genetic counseling; ii) their use for secondary preventiontechniques, (e.g., amniocentesis for prenatal diagnosis) in groups towhom techniques are ethically acceptable, iii) possible pertinence toidentification of producing aging effects upon adverse genetic outcomes.&quot;Simple&quot; genetic disorders must be distinguished from diseases whosegenetic contribution is more complex but not as certain quantitatively.</TEXT></DOC>